Processing output data from independent contrast regressions

Source: vignettes/articles/independent_contrast_regression_outputs.Rmd
independent_contrast_regression_outputs.Rmd

The main goal of the InNOutBT package is to readily create input data to and process output data from Meade & Pagel’s (2022) BayesTraits computer package.

Here in this article, we show how to use the package’s function BayesTraits.outputs for processing all output data from BayesTraits phylogenetic independent contrast regression analyses.

Setup

InNOutBT is not on CRAN yet but you can install the latest development version from GitHub:

#install.packages("devtools")
devtools::install_github("DBOSlab/InNOutBT")
library(InNOutBT)

Create sample of trait data using a different subset of explanatory variables

This function produces all BayesTraits input data of linked samples of trait/climate data (distribution data), by automatically generating two .txt files: one including the linked traits and the other with mean values for each included trait. The function also includes an argument to calculate the net node count for each species/accession given a phylogenetic tree of reference, which has been successfully used to explore the effect of speciation rates (e.g. O’Donovan et al. 2018) on the response variable.

The example below shows how to mine all accepted species for a specified vector of families.

library(InNOutBT)
BayesTraits.outputs(logst_dir = paste0(getwd(),"/BayesTraits_outputs_log_stone"),
                    responvar = "DBH",
                    explanvar = c("bio15"),
                    treetransf = c("Kappa", "Delta", "Lambda", "OU"),
                    bayesfactor = TRUE,
                    unirates = FALSE,
                    outformat = c("Word", "CSV"),
                    tableleg = "Phylogenetic regression in BayesTraits: models and coefficients.",
                    dir_create = "results_BayesTraits_output",
                    outfile = "BayesTraits_output_table",
                    height = 17,
                    width = 20)

Create sample of trait data using a different subset of explanatory variables

To mine a species checklist for all families of flowering plants, you recommend to load the dataframe-formatted data object called POWOcodes that comes associated with the expowo package. Because the POWOcodes data object already contains the URI addresses for all angiosperms families recognized in the POWO database, you do not need to perform the time-consuming URI search using taxize.

The example below shows how to mine a global checklist of all accepted species of flowering plants by using the vector of all angiosperm families and associated URI addresses stored in the POWOcodes object.

BayesTraits.outputs(logst_dir = paste0(getwd(),"/BayesTraits_outputs_log_stone"),
                    responvar = "DBH",
                    explanvar = c("bio15"),
                    treetransf = c("Kappa", "Delta", "Lambda", "OU"),
                    bayesfactor = TRUE,
                    unirates = FALSE,
                    outformat = c("Word", "CSV"),
                    tableleg = "Phylogenetic regression in BayesTraits: models and coefficients.",
                    dir_create = "results_BayesTraits_output",
                    outfile = "BayesTraits_output_table",
                    height = 17,
                    width = 20)
